It was founded in 1942 by {{ill|Shimizu Shin'ichi|ja|清水信一 (宗教家)}} ({{lang|ja|清水信一}}, 1910–1969), who is also known by his followers as {{nihongo|Beigan no Kuju|蔽顔の救主}} ({{lit|"Hidden Face Savior"}}). The religion considers him to be an incarnation of the Heavenly Savior (天降の救世寿), who had also manifested himself in the past as the Buddha, Jesus, Laozi, Confucius, and Muhammad.<ref>{{cite book |last= Yoshida (吉田) |first= Nobuo (演男) |date= 2011 |title= あまつさかえとこはに: 蔽顔の救主の御足跡を探ねて |url= |trans-title= The Heaven Thrives Eternally Unchanged: In Search for the Traces of the Hidden Face Savior |language= Japanese |location= [[Tokyo]] |publisher= [[:ja:今日の話題社|Kon'ichi No Wadaisha]] |isbn= 978-4875656036}}</ref>
Outside of Japan, there were attempts of proselytization to attract followers in South Korea.<ref>{{cite news |last= Jang (장) |first= Jeong-tae (정태) |date= 2017-05-22 |title= 일본 신종교 ‘천리교’ 고찰로 본 신종교 의미와 한국의 천리교 유입 ④ |trans-quote= Understanding the Meaning of New Religions and Tenrikyo Entering Korea through the Lense of the Japanese New Religion, Tenrikyo No.4 |url= https://www.crs-news.com/10448 |language= Korean |location= [[Seoul]] |publisher= Culture Religion Society News – Maeil Religion Newspaper |quote= 일본계 신종교가 한국에 처음 들어온 것은 1900년초 천리교이다. 해방 이후 … 천조광교, … 등이 들어왔다. 이 중에서 천리교와 일련정종이 크게 번창했다. |trans-quote= It was Tenrikyo that was the first Japanese new religion to enter Korea in the early 1900s. After the Liberation of Korea… Japanese new religions such as … Tensōkokyō … entered (South) Korea. Among the religions, Tenrikyo and Nichiren Shōshū thrived greatly (in South Korea).}}</ref>
==Teachings== It is a Shinto-based teachings that are heavily inspired by Buddhist and Christian teachings, particularly warning against immoral actions.{{#tag:ref|This is similar to the now-defunct [[Tenri Sanrinkō]]'s attempt to merge Buddhist and Christian teachings under a Shinto-inspired doctrinal context.<ref>{{cite book |last1= Umehara (梅原) |first1= Masaki (正紀) |author-link= :ja:梅原正紀 |last2= Mizuno (水野) |first2= Yoshiyuki (義之) |date= 1980 |title= 秘儀と霊能の世界: 新宗教の底流をさぐる |url= https://www.google.com/books/edition/%E7%A7%98%E5%84%80%E3%81%A8%E9%9C%8A%E8%83%BD%E3%81%AE%E4%B8%96%E7%95%8C/7f8xAQAAIAAJ |trans-title= The World of Secret Ceremonies & Psychic Capacities: Revealing the Underbelly of New Religions |language= Japanese |publisher= 紀尾井書房 |page= 85 |quote= 翌十一年ごろから、勝は仏教とキリスト教と天理教の教えを総合して「三教合一」の教義を樹立した。 |trans-quote= She (Katsu Hisano) formulated the doctrine of merging Buddhism, Christianity, and Tenrikyo together to form the United Teaching of Three Faiths (三教合一) starting around 1936.}}</ref>|group=n}}<ref>{{cite book |author= |editor-last1= Swanson |editor-first1= Paul L. |editor-last2= Chilson |editor-first2= Clark |date= 2005-10-31 |title= Nanzan Guide to Japanese Religions |url= https://www.google.co.kr/books/edition/Nanzan_Guide_to_Japanese_Religions/4vuHBV0FpIIC?hl=ko&gbpv=1&pg=PA125&printsec=frontcover |series= Nanzan Library of Asian Religion and Culture |volume= 6 |location= [[Honolulu]] |publisher= [[University of Hawaiʻi Press]] |page= 125 |isbn= 978-0824830021 |quote= Tensokōkyō 天祖光教, a messianic movement based in Nagoya, for example, draws on both Buddhist and Christian traditions.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= Whiting |first= Robert |date= 2009-09-26 |title= The Meaning of Ichiro: The New Wave from Japan and the Transformation of Our National Pastime |url= https://www.google.co.kr/books/edition/The_Meaning_of_Ichiro/jXplAgAAQBAJ |location= [[New York City]] |publisher= [[Grand Central Publishing]] |isbn= 978-0446565226 |quote= … Tenso Kōkyō, a nationwide religion that attempted to consolidate the teachings of Christianity, Buddhism, and Shintoism, admonishing its followers against greed, anger, gluttony, dishonesty and other evils proscribed by all three.}}</ref> The immoral actions are "greed, anger, gluttony, dishonesty and other evils" as designated by Shinto, Buddhism, and Christianity in unison.
==Scriptures== The religion's main scriptures, written by its founder, include ''Voice of the Sphinx'' (スフィンクスの声), as well as a collection of hymns known as the "Heavenly Sacred Hymns" (天降の聖歌).<ref>{{cite web | title=天祖光教について | website=宗教法人 天祖光教 | url=http://www.tensokokyo.or.jp/about.html | language=ja | access-date=2025-05-06}}</ref> Its [[mantra]] is {{nihongo|''Nichi-Nichi Ten Tō''|日日点灯}} ("everyday, lighting candles/lights") in full: {{lang|ja|日日点灯福寿無量天降救世主}}).<ref>{{cite web | title=よくあるご質問 | website=宗教法人 天祖光教 | url=http://www.tensokokyo.or.jp/faq.html | language=ja | access-date=2025-05-06}}</ref>
==Schisms== Rurikyō-kai ([[:ja:瑠璃教会|瑠璃教会]]), founded by Matsui Ruritoshi (松井瑠璃寿), split off from Tensokokyo in 1953.
